sourceQuestion:
In the given matrix

[-1  -2]
[ 0   1]
[ 1   2]

one of the eigenvalues is 1. The eigenvectors corresponding to the eigenvalue 1 are

A. {a(-2, 1) | a != 0, a in R}
B. {a(-2, 1) | a in R, a != 0}
C. {a(sqrt(2), 1) | a in R, a != 0}
D. {a(-sqrt(2), 1) | a in R, a != 0}

An array A contains n integers in locations A[0], A[1], ..., A[n-1]. It is required to shift the elements of the array cyclically to the left by K places, where 1 <= K <= n-1. An incomplete algorithm for doing this in linear time, without using another array is given below. Complete the algorithm by filling in the blanks. Assume all variables are suitably declared.

min := n;
i := 0;
while ___(1)___ do
  begin
    temp := A[i];
    j := i;
    while ___(2)___ do
      begin
        A[j] := A[(j+K) mod n];
        j := (j+K) mod n;
      end;
    A[j] := temp;
    i := i+1;
    min := min - ___(3)___;
  end;

A. (1) min > 0, (2) (j+K) mod n != i, (3) gcd(n, K)
B. (1) min > K, (2) (j+K) mod n != i, (3) n/gcd(n, K)
C. (1) min > 0, (2) (j-K+n) mod n != i, (3) n/gcd(n, K)
D. (1) min > K, (2) (j-K+n) mod n != i, (3) gcd(n, K)

